#: ../DISCOVER/11_inclusive_practices_during_checkin.md:14
msgid "Indicating pronouns:"
msgstr ""

#: ../DISCOVER/11_inclusive_practices_during_checkin.md:15
msgid ""
"Select a pin/button/ribbon for your lanyard to communicate your pronouns."
" Using a pin even if you don't feel like you need one helps create a "
"welcoming space for attendees who do."
msgstr ""

#: ../DISCOVER/11_inclusive_practices_during_checkin.md:16
msgid ""
"Color-coordinate the pins by pronoun for quicker recognition and "
"processing by those who see the pins. This lowers the barrier to checking"
" (look at the color)."
msgstr ""

#: ../DISCOVER/11_inclusive_practices_during_checkin.md:17
msgid ""
"Be sure to choose colors that works for folks with color-blindness. With "
"color-coded pins, needing to actually read them is a stress case rather "
"than the norm. Because people are used to the ease of the normal case, "
"they're more willing to take a little extra effort to read for the stress"
" cases. (purple: he, yellow: she, green: they, blue: ask)"
msgstr ""

#: ../DISCOVER/11_inclusive_practices_during_checkin.md:18
msgid ""
"To be aware of: Make pins large enough to be easily seen. Make the "
"pronoun itself the largest text, rather than the word "
"&quot;Pronouns&quot;."
msgstr ""

#: ../DISCOVER/11_inclusive_practices_during_checkin.md:19
msgid "Another option for pronoun indication is ribbons."
msgstr ""

#: ../DISCOVER/11_inclusive_practices_during_checkin.md:20
msgid ""
"Have custom ones printed for Zi/Zir and a \"Fill in your own\" ribbon. "
"For fill in your own, make sure you provide fabric markers. (h/t "
"@oxinabox)"
msgstr ""

